04068nam a22005775i 9780228010111DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280101117 a10.1515/97802280101112doi  a(DE-B1597)654752  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF3021.A59 7aPOL0570002bisacsh04a982.004/9272231 aRein, Raanan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPeronism as a Big Tent :bThe Political Inclusion of Arab Immigrants in Argentina /cRaanan Rein, Ariel Noyjovich. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b13 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in Ethnic History00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe Arrival of “Turcos” in Argentina -- t¡Viva Berón! The Political Integration of Arab-Argentines -- t“For an Arab, There Can Be Nothing Better Than Another Arab” -- tFrom Opening Railroad Stores to Running the Province: Arab Immigrants and the Peronization of Tucumán -- tThe “New Lords of the Levant” in Santiago del Estero and Their Support for Peronism -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aArgentina’s populist movement, led by Juan Perón, welcomed people from a broad range of cultural backgrounds to join its ranks. Unlike most populist movements in Europe and North America, Peronism had an inclusive nature, rejecting racism and xenophobia.In Peronism as a Big Tent Raanan Rein and Ariel Noyjovich examine Peronism’s attempts at garnering the support of Argentines of Middle Eastern origins – be they Jewish, Maronite, Orthodox Catholic, Druze, or Muslim – in both Buenos Aires and the interior provinces. By following the process that started with Perón’s administration in the mid-1940s and culminated with the 1989 election of President Carlos Menem, of Syrian parentage, Rein and Noyjovich paint a nuanced picture of Argentina’s journey from failed attempts to build a mosque in Buenos Aires in 1950 to the inauguration of the King Fahd Islamic Cultural Center in the nation’s capital in the year 2000.Peronism as a Big Tent reflects on Perón’s own evolution from perceiving Argentina as a Catholic country with little room for those outside the faith to embracing a vision of a society that was multicultural and that welcomed and celebrated religious plurality. The legacy of this spirit of inclusiveness can still be felt today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArabsxPolitical activityzArgentinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPeronismxHistoryy20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh  aArgentina.  aEthnicity.  aMiddle Eastern.  aMigrants.  aPeron.  aPopulism.1 aNoyjovich, Ariel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSadek, Isis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022801011140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228010111423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228010111/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles